+# 12. Profile-exponent interpolation: visible spectrum controls q_eff
+
+The coordinate-alignment theorem gives two extremes.  In aligned coordinates,
+RMSProp/Adam sees coordinate second moments proportional to the covariance
+eigenvalues and obtains
+
+\[
+    q_{\rm eff}=1/2.
+\]
+
+In globally mixed or flat coordinates, the coordinate second moments are nearly
+constant and the adaptive preconditioner is scalar at exponent level, so
+
+\[
+    q_{\rm eff}=0.
+\]
+
+This note proves an interpolation theorem.  If the coordinate second-moment
+profile scales like a power of the spectrum,
+
+\[
+    d_i\asymp \lambda_i^\theta,
+    \qquad 0\le \theta\le 1,
+\]
+
+then RMSProp/Adam has
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    q_{\rm eff}=\theta/2.
+}
+\]
+
+This gives a measurable bridge to experiments: estimate \(\theta\) from the
+coordinate variance profile and predict the optimizer-dependent scaling exponent.
+
+## 1. Visible-profile model
+
+Let
+
+\[
+    \lambda_i\asymp i^{-a},
+    \qquad a>1.
+\]
+
+Assume that, in the optimizer coordinates under consideration, the RMSProp/Adam
+second-moment estimator tracks a coordinate profile
+
+\[
+    v_i\asymp d\,d_i,
+\]
+
+where \(d>0\) is a scalar residual-energy factor and
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    d_i\asymp \lambda_i^\theta,
+    \qquad 0\le \theta\le1.
+}
+\]
+
+Here \(\theta\) quantifies how much spectral information is visible to the
+coordinatewise second moment.  The cases are:
+
+\[
+    \theta=1: \text{aligned or band-limited spectral coordinates},
+\]
+
+\[
+    \theta=0: \text{flat/global mixing coordinates}.
+\]
+
+After absorbing the scalar \(d^{-1/2}\) into the learning rate, the RMSProp/Adam
+preconditioner is
+
+\[
+    P_i\asymp (d_i+\rho)^{-1/2}
+    \asymp (\lambda_i^\theta+\rho)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+## 2. Effective spectrum
+
+The preconditioned covariance eigenvalue scale is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \mu_i^{\rho,\theta}
+    =
+    \lambda_i(\lambda_i^\theta+\rho)^{-1/2}.
+}
+\]
+
+If \(\lambda_i^\theta\gg \rho\), then
+
+\[
+    \mu_i^{\rho,\theta}\asymp \lambda_i^{1-\theta/2}.
+\]
+
+Since \(\lambda_i\asymp i^{-a}\), this gives
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \mu_i^{\rho,\theta}\asymp i^{-a(1-\theta/2)}
+    \qquad\text{before the damping knee.}
+}
+\]
+
+Thus the effective spectral exponent is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \alpha_{\rm eff}=a(1-\theta/2).
+}
+\]
+
+Equivalently,
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    q_{\rm eff}=1-\alpha_{\rm eff}/a=\theta/2.
+}
+\]
+
+## 3. Damping knee and learned-mode count
+
+The damping knee occurs when
+
+\[
+    \lambda_i^\theta\asymp \rho.
+\]
+
+Since \(\lambda_i\asymp i^{-a}\), the spectral knee is
+
+\[
+    i_\rho\asymp \rho^{-1/(a\theta)}
+    \qquad (\theta>0).
+\]
+
+At the knee,
+
+\[
+    \mu_{i_\rho}
+    \asymp
+    \lambda_{i_\rho}\rho^{-1/2}
+    \asymp
+    \rho^{1/\theta-1/2}.
+\]
+
+Therefore the sample-size knee is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    n_\rho\asymp \rho^{-(1/\theta-1/2)}.
+}
+\]
+
+The learned-mode count
+
+\[
+    K_{\rho,\theta}(n)=\#\{i:\mu_i^{\rho,\theta}\gtrsim n^{-1}\}
+\]
+
+satisfies
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+K_{\rho,\theta}(n)
+\asymp
+\begin{cases}
+    n^{1/[a(1-\theta/2)]},
+    & n\lesssim \rho^{-(1/\theta-1/2)},\\[4pt]
+    \rho^{-1/(2a)}n^{1/a},
+    & n\gtrsim \rho^{-(1/\theta-1/2)}.
+\end{cases}
+}
+\]
+
+For \(\theta=1\), this recovers the Adam/RMSProp count
+
+\[
+    K_{\rho,1}(n)
+    \asymp
+    \begin{cases}
+        n^{2/a}, & n\lesssim \rho^{-1/2},\\[3pt]
+        \rho^{-1/(2a)}n^{1/a}, & n\gtrsim \rho^{-1/2}.
+    \end{cases}
+\]
+
+For \(\theta=0\), the profile is flat and
+
+\[
+    \mu_i\asymp \lambda_i,
+    \qquad
+    K(n)\asymp n^{1/a},
+\]
+
+up to constants.
+
+## 4. Risk scaling in the clean source range
+
+Assume the source condition
+
+\[
+    s_i=\lambda_i(w_i^\star)^2\asymp i^{-b}.
+\]
+
+In the clean range
+
+\[
+    1<b<a(1-\theta/2)+1,
+\]
+
+the same filter lower-bound calculus gives
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    R_M-\sigma^2
+    \asymp
+    M^{1-b}
+    +K_{\rho,\theta}(n)^{1-b}
+    +\frac{\min\{M,K_{\rho,\theta}(n)\}}{N_{\rm eff}}.
+}
+\]
+
+Before the damping knee and when variance is lower order, this simplifies to
+
+\[
+    R_M-\sigma^2
+    \asymp
+    M^{1-b}
+    +n^{-(b-1)/[a(1-\theta/2)]}.
+\]
+
+Thus the data-scaling exponent improves continuously as more spectral
+information becomes visible to the coordinatewise second moment.
+
+## 5. Experimental prediction
+
+Given a feature map or sketch with trainable-coordinate covariance \(\Sigma\),
+compute
+
+\[
+    d_j=\Sigma_{jj}.
+\]
+
+If the coordinates have a meaningful spectral order or band order, fit
+
+\[
+    d_j\asymp j^{-a\theta}.
+\]
+
+Then predict
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    q_{\rm eff}\approx \theta/2,
+    \qquad
+    \alpha_{\rm eff}\approx a(1-\theta/2).
+}
+\]
+
+A profile slope alone is not always sufficient: if the diagonal profile is not
+aligned with eigenspaces, the preconditioner may not commute with the covariance.
+The next note gives a spectral-comparability criterion that separates true
+spectral visibility from accidental sorted-diagonal variation.
