+# 13. Gaussian sketches flatten coordinate moments
+
+This note applies the coordinate-alignment theory to Gaussian sketches.  It
+shows that a fully isotropic Gaussian sketch tends to flatten the coordinatewise
+second moments seen by RMSProp/Adam.  Therefore, in such sketch coordinates,
+diagonal adaptivity is often scalar at exponent level rather than an oracle
+spectral preconditioner.
+
+## 1. Sketched covariance
+
+Let the original covariance be
+
+\[
+    H=\operatorname{diag}(\lambda_1,\ldots,\lambda_d),
+\]
+
+and let the trainable features be
+
+\[
+    z=Sx,
+\]
+
+where \(S\in\mathbb R^{m\times d}\).  The covariance in trainable coordinates is
+
+\[
+    \Sigma=SHS^\top.
+\]
+
+RMSProp/Adam tracks coordinate second moments proportional to
+
+\[
+    d_j=\Sigma_{jj}=s_j^\top Hs_j,
+\]
+
+where \(s_j\) is row \(j\) of \(S\).
+
+## 2. Isotropic Gaussian sketch rows
+
+Assume
+
+\[
+    s_j\sim \mathcal N(0,I_d/d)
+\]
+
+independently across rows.  Then
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \mathbb E d_j=\frac{\operatorname{tr}(H)}{d}.
+}
+\]
+
+Moreover,
+
+\[
+    d_j=\frac1d\sum_{i=1}^d \lambda_i g_i^2,
+    \qquad g_i\sim\mathcal N(0,1).
+\]
+
+Define the effective rank
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    r_{\rm eff}(H)
+    =
+    \frac{\operatorname{tr}(H)^2}{\operatorname{tr}(H^2)}.
+}
+\]
+
+Weighted chi-square concentration gives universal constants \(c,C>0\) such that
+for \(t\in(0,1)\),
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    \mathbb P\left(
+        |d_j-\operatorname{tr}(H)/d|
+        \ge
+        t\operatorname{tr}(H)/d
+    \right)
+    \le
+    2\exp[-ct^2 r_{\rm eff}(H)].
+}
+\]
+
+A union bound gives uniform flattening over all sketch coordinates when
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    r_{\rm eff}(H)\gtrsim t^{-2}\log(m/\delta).
+}
+\]
+
+Then, with probability at least \(1-\delta\),
+
+\[
+    (1-t)\frac{\operatorname{tr}(H)}d
+    \le
+    d_j
+    \le
+    (1+t)\frac{\operatorname{tr}(H)}d
+    \qquad\text{for all }j\le m.
+\]
+
+## 3. Consequence for Adam/RMSProp
+
+On the flattening event,
+
+\[
+    P_j=(d_j+\rho)^{-1/2}
+\]
+
+is constant up to factors depending only on \(t\).  Thus
+
+\[
+    P\asymp c_\rho I,
+\]
+
+and
+
+\[
+    P^{1/2}\Sigma P^{1/2}\asymp c_\rho\Sigma.
+\]
+
+Therefore the eigenvalue decay exponent of the transformed covariance is the
+same as the eigenvalue decay exponent of \(\Sigma\).  In this regime,
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+    q_{\rm eff}=0
+    \qquad\text{for coordinatewise Adam/RMSProp in sketch coordinates.}
+}
+\]
+
+So a fully isotropic Gaussian sketch can wash out the coordinatewise spectral
+information needed for Adam/RMSProp to realize the aligned-coordinate
+\(q_{\rm eff}=1/2\) scaling.
+
+## 4. Low effective-rank caveat
+
+When \(H\) has very low effective rank, the diagonal entries \(d_j
+=s_j^\top Hs_j\) can fluctuate substantially.  However, these fluctuations are
+random quadratic-form fluctuations, not ordered spectral bands.  A sorted
+profile of \(d_j\) may have a nonzero slope, but the diagonal preconditioner need
+not commute with \(\Sigma\).  The relevant diagnostic is therefore not only the
+slope of sorted \(d_j\), but also whether the diagonal preconditioner is
+spectrally comparable to a function of \(\Sigma\).  The spectral-comparability
+criterion in the next note formalizes this.
+
+## 5. Research implication
+
+For the original Gaussian-sketched linear model, diagonal Adam/RMSProp should not
+be expected to automatically behave like oracle spectral preconditioning.  To
+obtain an optimizer-dependent exponent improvement, the trainable coordinates
+must retain spectral-band information.  This suggests comparing:
+
+1. isotropic Gaussian sketches, predicted to have \(q_{\rm eff}\approx0\);
+2. band-limited or structured sketches, predicted to have \(q_{\rm eff}\approx1/2\);
+3. intermediate sketches, predicted to have \(q_{\rm eff}\in(0,1/2)\) when their
+   preconditioners are spectrally comparable to \((\Sigma^\theta+\rho I)^{-1/2}\).
